insert into public.concepts
  (id, term, aliases, said, alias_list, status, one_liner, analogy, example, related, deeper, lens_pm, lens_eng, domain, priority, tags)
values
  ('hnsw', 'HNSW', 'Hierarchical Navigable Small World', '', ARRAY['hnsw','hierarchical navigable small world']::text[], 'Core', 'The graph trick most vector databases use to find close matches fast without checking every item.', 'Finding a house by hopping between well-connected neighbors instead of knocking on every door in the city.', 'When Pinecone or Qdrant returns your top matches in milliseconds over millions of vectors, HNSW is usually the reason.', '[{"text":"The most common way to do approximate nearest neighbor search.","id":"approximate-nearest-neighbor"},{"text":"Powers the search inside most vector databases.","id":"vectordatabase"}]'::jsonb, 'HNSW builds a layered graph where each vector links to its nearest neighbors, with sparse express lanes on top for big jumps. A search drops in at the top, greedily walks toward the query, and descends layer by layer. It trades a small chance of missing the true nearest neighbor for enormous speed — you tune that trade with parameters like ef and M.', 'It is why semantic search feels instant even at scale, and why more accuracy costs more memory and latency.', 'A multi-layer proximity graph traversed greedily; recall and latency are tuned via ef_search, ef_construction, and M.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('approximate-nearest-neighbor', 'Approximate Nearest Neighbor', 'ANN', '', ARRAY['approximate nearest neighbor','ann']::text[], 'Core', 'Finding items that are almost certainly the closest, without the cost of proving it.', 'Asking a few locals for the nearest gas station instead of surveying every road on the map.', 'A search over 50 million product embeddings returns in 10ms because it settles for "very close" rather than "provably closest".', '[{"text":"HNSW is the most popular algorithm for it.","id":"hnsw"},{"text":"The honest, slower alternative that checks everything.","id":"exact-nearest-neighbor"}]'::jsonb, 'Exact search means comparing your query to every stored vector — fine for thousands, hopeless for millions. ANN methods build clever indexes that skip most comparisons and return the top matches with high probability. You accept a tiny recall loss for orders-of-magnitude speedup, and you can dial the trade-off.', 'It is the reason large-scale semantic features are affordable at all; the "approximate" rarely shows up in user experience.', 'Sublinear-time retrieval via graph or partition indexes; recall is a tunable parameter, not a guarantee.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('exact-nearest-neighbor', 'Exact Nearest Neighbor', 'Brute-Force Search', '', ARRAY['exact nearest neighbor','brute-force search','exact knn']::text[], 'Rising', 'Actually comparing your query against every item to find the true closest — correct, but it does not scale.', 'Reading every résumé in the pile to find the best fit, instead of trusting a filter.', 'For a few thousand FAQ entries, a startup just loops over all of them — no index needed, no recall loss.', '[{"text":"The scalable, slightly lossy alternative.","id":"approximate-nearest-neighbor"},{"text":"Compares vectors using a distance measure.","id":"vector-similarity"}]'::jsonb, 'Exact search computes the distance to every stored vector and keeps the smallest. It is perfectly accurate and dead simple, which makes it the right choice for small collections or as a correctness baseline. The catch is linear cost: double the data, double the work, so past a certain size everyone reaches for approximate methods.', 'Great for small datasets or when you cannot tolerate any miss; a trap if your data is going to grow.', 'O(n) scan with a top-k heap; used as ground truth to measure an ANN index’s recall.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('metadata-filtering', 'Metadata Filtering', 'Filtered Search', '', ARRAY['metadata filtering','filtered search']::text[], 'Core', 'Narrowing a vector search by plain attributes — date, author, tenant — before or during the similarity match.', 'Telling the librarian "only books from this decade" before asking which is most relevant.', 'A support bot retrieves only docs tagged for the customer’s product tier, so a free user never sees enterprise-only answers.', '[{"text":"Combines with vector similarity inside the store.","id":"vector-similarity"},{"text":"Runs inside the vector database.","id":"vectordatabase"}]'::jsonb, 'Embeddings capture meaning but not hard facts like "belongs to org 42" or "published after 2024". Metadata filters attach those as structured fields and restrict the candidate set. The tricky part is when filtering happens: pre-filtering is precise but can starve the index, while post-filtering is fast but may throw away most of your top-k before you get enough matches.', 'It is how one shared search index safely serves many customers, permissions, and freshness rules.', 'Boolean predicates over payload fields, applied pre- or post-ANN; pre-filtering interacts badly with graph indexes if selectivity is high.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('short-term-memory', 'Short-Term Memory', 'Working Memory (LLM)', '', ARRAY['short-term memory']::text[], 'Core', 'What the model can "remember" right now — everything sitting in the current context window.', 'The notes spread on your desk during a meeting: instantly available, but swept away when you leave the room.', 'A chatbot recalls what you said three messages ago because it is all still in the prompt — not because it learned anything.', '[{"text":"Lives entirely inside the context window.","id":"contextwindow"},{"text":"The running transcript that fills it.","id":"conversation-history"}]'::jsonb, 'Models have no memory between calls; "short-term memory" is just the tokens you feed in this turn. It is fast and lossless while it lasts, but bounded by the context window and gone the moment the conversation is trimmed or a new session starts. Anything you want kept longer has to be written somewhere and retrieved later.', 'It sets how much a session can "hold in its head" before you must persist and retrieve context yourself.', 'Non-persistent state = the current token sequence; nothing survives outside the request without external storage.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('conversation-history', 'Conversation History', 'Chat History', '', ARRAY['conversation history','chat history']::text[], 'Core', 'The running transcript of a chat that gets replayed to the model so it stays coherent.', 'Re-reading the whole email thread before you reply so you do not repeat yourself.', 'Each time you send a message, the app resends the prior turns so the assistant "remembers" your name from earlier.', '[{"text":"Fills the model’s short-term memory.","id":"short-term-memory"},{"text":"Gets compressed once it grows too long.","id":"summarization-memory"}]'::jsonb, 'Because models are stateless, the app rebuilds the conversation each turn by prepending previous messages. This works until the history outgrows the context window, at which point you must trim old turns, summarize them, or retrieve only the relevant bits. Naively keeping everything is the most common cause of ballooning token costs.', 'Every remembered detail is a resent token you pay for; long chats quietly get expensive and slow.', 'Stateless inference re-hydrated per request; token budget forces truncation, summarization, or selective retrieval.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('summarization-memory', 'Summarization Memory', 'Memory Compression', '', ARRAY['summarization memory','memory compression']::text[], 'Rising', 'Squeezing old conversation into a short recap so a long chat still fits in the window.', 'Replacing a two-hour meeting with a five-line minutes doc you can skim later.', 'After 40 messages, the app quietly compresses the early ones into "User is planning a Japan trip in October, budget-conscious, vegetarian."', '[{"text":"Compresses the conversation history.","id":"conversation-history"},{"text":"A workaround for the context window limit.","id":"contextwindow"}]'::jsonb, 'When history won’t fit, you summarize the oldest turns into a compact note and keep only that plus recent messages. It buys room but leaks detail — the summary decides what survives, and anything it drops is effectively forgotten. Good systems summarize hierarchically and keep raw text retrievable in case the recap missed something.', 'Lets long-running assistants feel continuous, at the cost of occasionally forgetting a detail the summary skipped.', 'Recursive summarization of stale turns; lossy compression traded against context budget, ideally paired with retrievable raw logs.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('knowledge-base', 'Knowledge Base', 'KB', '', ARRAY['knowledge base','kb']::text[], 'Core', 'The curated pile of documents a system searches to answer questions with real facts.', 'The company handbook everyone points to instead of guessing the policy.', 'A support assistant is wired to a knowledge base of help articles, so its answers cite your actual docs, not the open internet.', '[{"text":"What a RAG system retrieves from.","id":"rag"},{"text":"Stored and chunked for retrieval.","id":"document-store"}]'::jsonb, 'A knowledge base is the source of truth a retrieval system draws on — help docs, policies, product specs, past tickets. Its quality caps the whole system: stale, contradictory, or missing content produces confident-but-wrong answers no matter how good the model is. Curating and refreshing it is ongoing work, not a one-time load.', 'The answer quality ceiling; investing in clean, current content beats most model tweaks.', 'The corpus feeding ingestion and retrieval; freshness and dedup are operational, not one-shot, concerns.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('graphrag', 'GraphRAG', 'Graph-based RAG', '', ARRAY['graphrag','graph rag','graph-based rag']::text[], 'Rising', 'RAG that first builds a graph of entities and relationships, so it can answer questions plain chunk-search can’t.', 'Instead of skimming loose pages, drawing the org chart first so you can trace who reports to whom.', 'Asked "how are these three suppliers connected?", GraphRAG walks the relationship graph rather than hoping one chunk mentions all three.', '[{"text":"A structured extension of ordinary RAG.","id":"rag"},{"text":"Still relies on retrieval over the graph.","id":"retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Standard RAG retrieves independent chunks, which struggles with questions that span many documents or need a global view. GraphRAG extracts entities and relations into a knowledge graph, often clusters it into summarized communities, and retrieves over that structure. It shines on "connect the dots" and whole-corpus questions, but building and maintaining the graph is real extra cost and complexity.', 'Worth it when users ask synthesis questions across a big corpus; overkill for simple lookup FAQs.', 'Entity/relation extraction into a graph plus community summaries, retrieved via graph traversal rather than flat top-k.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('dense-retrieval', 'Dense Retrieval', 'Embedding Retrieval', '', ARRAY['dense retrieval','embedding retrieval']::text[], 'Core', 'Finding documents by meaning, using embeddings, so "car trouble" can match "engine won’t start".', 'A helpful clerk who understands what you mean, not just the exact words you said.', 'A search for "how do I cancel" surfaces the "ending your subscription" article even though no words overlap.', '[{"text":"Powered by embeddings.","id":"embeddings"},{"text":"Contrasts with sparse, word-matching retrieval.","id":"sparse-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Dense retrieval encodes both query and documents into vectors and matches on similarity in that space, capturing synonyms and paraphrase. The strength is semantic recall; the weakness is that rare exact terms — a part number, a name — can get blurred away. That is why it is often paired with sparse methods in a hybrid setup.', 'Makes search forgiving of how users phrase things; can miss precise codes and jargon on its own.', 'Bi-encoder embeddings + ANN over a vector store; strong on semantics, weak on exact-token and long-tail matches.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('sparse-retrieval', 'Sparse Retrieval', 'Lexical Retrieval', '', ARRAY['sparse retrieval','lexical retrieval']::text[], 'Core', 'Finding documents by the actual words they share with your query — old-school, but precise.', 'Ctrl-F across every document, weighted so rare words count more than common ones.', 'Searching an exact error code "ERR_0x8007" returns the one doc that literally contains it, no semantics required.', '[{"text":"BM25 is the classic scoring method.","id":"bm25"},{"text":"Contrasts with meaning-based dense retrieval.","id":"dense-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Sparse retrieval represents text as high-dimensional word-count vectors (mostly zeros, hence "sparse") and scores overlap, classically with BM25. It nails exact terms, rare identifiers, and jargon, but it is literal — it misses synonyms and paraphrase entirely. Modern systems keep it around precisely because dense embeddings are bad at the things sparse is great at.', 'Reliable for precise, keyword-heavy queries; blind to meaning, so pair it with dense for best coverage.', 'Bag-of-words term weighting (TF-IDF/BM25) over an inverted index; exact-match strong, semantically blind.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('lexical-search', 'Lexical Search', 'Term-based Search', '', ARRAY['lexical search','term-based search']::text[], 'Core', 'Search that matches literal words and their forms, not underlying meaning.', 'A dictionary lookup: it finds the word you typed, not the idea you had.', 'A legal search for the exact phrase "force majeure" returns only documents containing those words.', '[{"text":"Implemented with sparse retrieval methods.","id":"sparse-retrieval"},{"text":"Often blended with semantic search.","id":"semantic-search"}]'::jsonb, 'Lexical search compares the tokens in your query to tokens in documents, usually with stemming and stopword handling, then ranks by term frequency and rarity. It is transparent, fast, and precise for known terms, which is why it powered search for decades. Its blind spot is language variation — different words for the same concept simply do not match.', 'Predictable and explainable, ideal when users know the exact term; frustrating when they paraphrase.', 'Token-level matching over an inverted index with stemming/analysis; no semantic generalization.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('keyword-search', 'Keyword Search', 'Keyword Matching', '', ARRAY['keyword search','keyword matching']::text[], 'Core', 'The plain "match these words" search everyone already knows from the web.', 'Typing words into a search box and getting back pages that contain them.', 'A user types "invoice pdf export" and gets docs mentioning those words, ranked by how strongly they match.', '[{"text":"A form of lexical search.","id":"lexical-search"},{"text":"Complemented by meaning-based semantic search.","id":"semantic-search"}]'::jsonb, 'Keyword search ranks documents by how well their words match the query, typically via inverted indexes and frequency-based scoring. It is the familiar baseline: cheap, fast, and good when the user’s words match the content’s words. It falls down on synonyms, misspellings, and intent — which is why "just add keyword search" is rarely the whole answer anymore.', 'A dependable floor for search quality and a sanity check against fancier methods; not sufficient alone for natural questions.', 'Inverted-index term matching with frequency scoring; the lexical half of most hybrid stacks.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('query-expansion', 'Query Expansion', 'Query Enrichment', '', ARRAY['query expansion','query enrichment']::text[], 'Rising', 'Quietly adding synonyms and related terms to a search so it catches documents worded differently.', 'Asking for "soda" and having the waiter also check for "pop" and "fizzy drink".', 'A search for "laptop won’t charge" is expanded with "battery", "power adapter", "not powering on" to widen the net.', '[{"text":"A cousin of query rewriting.","id":"query-rewriting"},{"text":"Boosts recall before retrieval.","id":"retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Query expansion augments the original query with extra terms — from synonyms, related searches, or an LLM — to improve recall when the corpus uses different vocabulary. It helps sparse methods most, since those depend on exact overlap. The risk is drift: add too many loosely related terms and you dredge up irrelevant results, hurting precision.', 'Catches answers users would otherwise miss due to wording, at some risk of noisier results.', 'Augment the query with synonyms/related terms (thesaurus, PRF, or LLM-generated); raises recall, can dent precision.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('query-rewriting', 'Query Rewriting', 'Query Reformulation', '', ARRAY['query rewriting','query reformulation']::text[], 'Rising', 'Rephrasing a messy or context-dependent question into a cleaner one before searching.', 'A good assistant turning "what about the other one?" into "what are the specs of the 15-inch model?" before acting.', 'In a chat, "and its price?" gets rewritten to "what is the price of the MacBook Air M3?" using earlier context, so retrieval actually works.', '[{"text":"Related to query expansion.","id":"query-expansion"},{"text":"Often precedes retrieval in the pipeline.","id":"retrieval-pipeline"}]'::jsonb, 'Follow-up questions and vague phrasing wreck retrieval because the search sees only the latest words. Query rewriting uses the conversation or an LLM to produce a self-contained, well-formed query. Done well it dramatically improves multi-turn search; done carelessly it can inject assumptions the user never made and quietly change what they asked.', 'The unsung fix that makes chat-style search actually work across turns.', 'LLM- or rule-based reformulation to a standalone query; conditioning on history resolves coreference and ellipsis.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('hypothetical-document-embeddings', 'Hypothetical Document Embeddings', 'HyDE method', '', ARRAY['hypothetical document embeddings']::text[], 'Rising', 'Search by first imagining the answer, then finding real documents that look like it.', 'Sketching what the missing puzzle piece should look like, then hunting for the piece that matches your sketch.', 'For "why is my sourdough dense?", the model drafts a plausible answer, embeds that, and retrieves real baking docs similar to the draft.', '[{"text":"Better known by its acronym, HyDE.","id":"hyde"},{"text":"Improves dense retrieval on hard queries.","id":"dense-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'Short queries embed poorly because they carry little signal. This technique asks an LLM to generate a hypothetical answer, embeds that richer text, and retrieves against it — the fake document is closer in vector space to the real ones than the bare query was. It boosts recall on tough questions, but if the model hallucinates the wrong kind of answer, it can steer retrieval astray.', 'A clever recall boost for vague or terse queries; adds an LLM call and can misfire if the draft is off-base.', 'Generate a pseudo-answer, embed it, retrieve by its vector; bridges the query–document distribution gap in dense retrieval.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('hyde', 'HyDE', 'Hypothetical Document Embeddings', '“hide”', ARRAY['hyde','hyde retrieval']::text[], 'Rising', 'The catchy name for retrieving with an imagined answer instead of the raw question.', 'Guessing what the answer key says, then finding the textbook page that matches your guess.', 'A research tool uses HyDE so that "effects of microplastics on soil" pulls papers matching a drafted summary, not just the keywords.', '[{"text":"The full name and mechanism.","id":"hypothetical-document-embeddings"},{"text":"A trick layered onto standard retrieval.","id":"retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'HyDE is shorthand for Hypothetical Document Embeddings: prompt an LLM for a plausible answer, embed it, and use that vector to retrieve. It reliably lifts zero-shot dense retrieval because generated prose sits nearer the target documents than a short query does. The trade is an extra generation step and sensitivity to the draft’s quality.', 'Same idea as its longer name — worth trying when short queries retrieve poorly.', 'LLM-drafted pseudo-doc embedded for retrieval; strong zero-shot gains, dependent on generation fidelity.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('passage-retrieval', 'Passage Retrieval', 'Passage Search', '', ARRAY['passage retrieval','passage search']::text[], 'Core', 'Fetching the specific paragraphs that answer a question, not whole documents.', 'Highlighting the exact sentences in a report instead of handing someone the entire binder.', 'Asked about a refund window, the system returns the one paragraph stating "30 days", not the full 40-page policy.', '[{"text":"Depends on how documents are chunked.","id":"chunking"},{"text":"The retrieval step feeding a RAG answer.","id":"rag"}]'::jsonb, 'Whole documents are too big and too diluted to hand a model; passage retrieval works at the paragraph or chunk level so the relevant bit lands in context. Granularity is the whole game: too coarse and you waste context on filler, too fine and you sever the sentence that gives an answer its meaning. It is the retrieval half of most question-answering systems.', 'Precise passages mean tighter, better-grounded answers and lower token cost than dumping full docs.', 'Chunk-level dense/sparse retrieval; answer quality hinges on chunk granularity and boundary choices.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('document-store', 'Document Store', 'Doc Store', '', ARRAY['document store','doc store']::text[], 'Core', 'Where the raw text and chunks actually live, so retrieval can pull them back on demand.', 'The filing cabinet behind the front-desk index cards — the cards point, the cabinet holds the real papers.', 'The vector index returns chunk IDs; the document store hands back the actual paragraph text to stuff into the prompt.', '[{"text":"Paired with a vector database index.","id":"vectordatabase"},{"text":"Holds the chunks produced by chunking.","id":"chunking"}]'::jsonb, 'A retrieval system usually separates the index (vectors for finding things) from the store (the text itself). The store keeps original chunks, metadata, and IDs so that once search identifies a match, you can fetch the exact content to show or feed the model. Some databases fuse the two; conceptually they play different roles, and keeping the source text intact matters for citations.', 'The system of record for what your assistant actually quotes; keep it clean and traceable.', 'Persistent chunk+metadata storage keyed by ID, decoupled from the ANN index that references it.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('index', 'Index', 'Search Index', '', ARRAY['index','search index']::text[], 'Core', 'The prebuilt structure that lets you find matching items fast instead of scanning everything.', 'The index at the back of a textbook — you jump straight to the page instead of reading cover to cover.', 'Adding an HNSW index turns a search that scanned millions of vectors into one that touches a few thousand.', '[{"text":"HNSW is a popular vector index type.","id":"hnsw"},{"text":"The inverted index is its lexical cousin.","id":"inverted-index"}]'::jsonb, 'An index reorganizes data so lookups skip most of it — a graph for vectors, an inverted list for words. Building one costs time and memory up front and must be maintained as data changes, but it converts slow linear scans into fast, targeted retrieval. Every retrieval system is, at heart, a choice of what to index and how.', 'The difference between "search feels instant" and "search times out"; not free to build or keep fresh.', 'Auxiliary structure (graph, tree, inverted list) trading build/memory cost for sublinear query time.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('inverted-index', 'Inverted Index', 'Postings List', '', ARRAY['inverted index','postings list']::text[], 'Core', 'A word-to-documents map that makes keyword search fast — the backbone of classic search engines.', 'A book index listing, for each word, every page it appears on.', 'Elasticsearch stores, for the word "refund", the list of every document ID containing it, so lookups are near-instant.', '[{"text":"The engine behind lexical search.","id":"lexical-search"},{"text":"A specific kind of index.","id":"index"}]'::jsonb, 'Instead of storing "document → words", an inverted index stores "word → documents", with positions and frequencies. To answer a query you intersect the lists for each term and score by relevance, typically BM25. It is decades-old technology and still unbeatable for exact-term retrieval, which is why hybrid systems keep it beside their shiny vector index.', 'Why keyword search scales to billions of docs; the reliable half of a hybrid stack.', 'Term → postings mapping with positions/frequencies; list intersection plus BM25 scoring drives lexical retrieval.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('recall-at-k', 'Recall at K', 'Recall@K', '', ARRAY['recall at k','recall@k']::text[], 'Core', 'Of all the right answers out there, how many showed up in your top K results.', 'Casting a net and asking: of all the fish in the pond you wanted, how many did you actually pull up?', 'If a query has 4 relevant docs and 3 appear in the top 10, recall@10 is 0.75.', '[{"text":"The precision counterpart.","id":"precision-at-k"},{"text":"A core measure of retrieval quality.","id":"retrieval-quality"}]'::jsonb, 'Recall@K measures coverage: did retrieval surface the relevant items within the first K? It matters most in RAG, where a missed passage means the model literally cannot answer. High recall usually comes at the cost of precision — a bigger K catches more truth but also more noise, which then leans on reranking to sort out.', 'If recall is low, no amount of prompt tuning helps — the answer never reached the model.', '|relevant ∩ top-K| / |relevant|; the recall/precision trade-off is set by K and the retriever.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('precision-at-k', 'Precision at K', 'Precision@K', '', ARRAY['precision at k','precision@k']::text[], 'Core', 'Of the top K results you returned, how many were actually relevant.', 'Of the ten job candidates you shortlisted, how many were genuinely qualified.', 'If 8 of your top 10 retrieved chunks are on-topic, precision@10 is 0.8; the other two are noise the model must ignore.', '[{"text":"The recall counterpart.","id":"recall-at-k"},{"text":"Reranking exists to raise it.","id":"reranking"}]'::jsonb, 'Precision@K measures how clean your top results are. In RAG it matters because irrelevant chunks waste context tokens and can distract the model into wrong answers. Precision and recall pull against each other, which is why pipelines retrieve broadly for recall, then rerank to push precision up in the final few passed to the model.', 'Low precision means the model wades through junk; it shows up as vague or off-topic answers.', '|relevant ∩ top-K| / K; typically maximized via a reranking stage after high-recall retrieval.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('retrieval-quality', 'Retrieval Quality', 'Retrieval Effectiveness', '', ARRAY['retrieval quality','retrieval effectiveness']::text[], 'Core', 'How good your search actually is at surfacing the right stuff — the ceiling on any RAG answer.', 'A cook can only be as good as the ingredients delivered; bad groceries, bad dinner.', 'A RAG bot gives wrong answers not because the model is dumb but because retrieval keeps handing it the wrong paragraphs.', '[{"text":"Measured by recall and precision at K.","id":"recall-at-k"},{"text":"Caps how well RAG can perform.","id":"rag"}]'::jsonb, 'Retrieval quality is the composite of recall, precision, and ranking — do the right passages show up, and near the top? It is the most common and most overlooked failure point in RAG: teams tune prompts for weeks when the real problem is that the relevant chunk never gets retrieved. Measuring it with real queries is the fastest way to find where a system is actually broken.', 'Fix retrieval before blaming the model; it is usually where quality problems really live.', 'Aggregate of recall@K, precision@K, and rank position; the upstream bottleneck for grounded generation.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('chunk-size', 'Chunk Size', 'Chunk Length', '', ARRAY['chunk size','chunk length']::text[], 'Core', 'How big each piece of a document is when you split it for retrieval — a surprisingly high-stakes knob.', 'Cutting a sandwich: too big to fit the box, too small and the filling falls out.', 'A team switches from 1000-token chunks to 300-token ones and suddenly answers get sharper because passages are more focused.', '[{"text":"A key parameter of chunking.","id":"chunking"},{"text":"Directly affects retrieval quality.","id":"retrieval-quality"}]'::jsonb, 'Chunk size trades context for precision. Large chunks keep surrounding meaning but dilute the embedding and waste tokens; small chunks are precise but can strand a fact from the sentence that explains it. There is no universal best — it depends on content and query style — so it is one of the first things worth tuning, often with a bit of overlap between chunks.', 'One of the cheapest levers on answer quality; worth experimenting with early.', 'Token/char span per chunk; governs embedding specificity vs. context retention, usually tuned with overlap.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('sentence-splitting', 'Sentence Splitting', 'Sentence Segmentation', '', ARRAY['sentence splitting','sentence segmentation']::text[], 'Core', 'Cutting text at sentence boundaries so chunks don’t start or end mid-thought.', 'Tearing a page along the perforations instead of ripping through the middle of a line.', 'A chunker uses sentence splitting so "The dose is 5mg. Do not exceed" never gets severed between "5mg" and "Do not exceed".', '[{"text":"A building block of chunking.","id":"chunking"},{"text":"Feeds into semantic chunking.","id":"semantic-chunking"}]'::jsonb, 'Naively slicing every N characters can cut a sentence in half, garbling both pieces. Sentence splitting detects boundaries — trickier than it sounds, thanks to "Dr.", "3.14", and abbreviations — and packs whole sentences into chunks. It is the humble preprocessing step that keeps retrieved passages readable and meaning intact.', 'Unglamorous but real: clean boundaries mean chunks the model can actually use.', 'Boundary detection (rules or ML) to avoid mid-sentence cuts; edge cases are abbreviations, decimals, and quotes.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('recursive-chunking', 'Recursive Chunking', 'Recursive Splitting', '', ARRAY['recursive chunking','recursive splitting']::text[], 'Rising', 'Splitting text by trying big separators first — paragraphs, then sentences — until pieces fit.', 'Breaking a chocolate bar along the deepest grooves first, snapping smaller only if the piece is still too big.', 'A splitter tries paragraph breaks, and only where a paragraph is too long does it drop to sentence-level cuts.', '[{"text":"A strategy within chunking.","id":"chunking"},{"text":"Respects natural structure like sentence splitting.","id":"sentence-splitting"}]'::jsonb, 'Recursive chunking uses an ordered list of separators — say, double newlines, then newlines, then spaces — and applies each in turn until chunks are under the size limit. This keeps semantically coherent units together when possible and only makes ugly cuts as a last resort. It is the default in many frameworks because it is simple and respects document structure better than fixed slicing.', 'A sensible default that keeps chunks coherent without much tuning.', 'Hierarchical separator list applied top-down until the size constraint is met; balances structure and length.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('semantic-chunking', 'Semantic Chunking', 'Meaning-based Chunking', '', ARRAY['semantic chunking','meaning-based chunking']::text[], 'Rising', 'Splitting text where the topic shifts, not at fixed lengths, so each chunk is one coherent idea.', 'Cutting a movie into scenes by where the story turns, not every ten minutes on the clock.', 'A doc about "install, then configure, then troubleshoot" gets split at each topic change, so retrieval returns just the troubleshooting part.', '[{"text":"A smarter alternative to fixed chunk size.","id":"chunk-size"},{"text":"Uses embeddings to detect topic shifts.","id":"embeddings"}]'::jsonb, 'Semantic chunking embeds consecutive sentences and places a boundary wherever similarity drops — the signal that the topic changed. The payoff is chunks that align to ideas rather than arbitrary token counts, which usually improves retrieval. The cost is more compute up front and sensitivity to the threshold, so it is not always worth it over simpler recursive splitting.', 'Can lift retrieval quality on messy docs; adds preprocessing cost, so measure before adopting.', 'Boundary placement via drops in inter-sentence embedding similarity; threshold-sensitive and compute-heavier than fixed splits.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('embedding-dimension', 'Embedding Dimension', 'Vector Dimensionality', '', ARRAY['embedding dimension','vector dimensionality','embedding dimensions']::text[], 'Core', 'How many numbers each embedding uses — more can mean richer meaning but heavier storage.', 'Describing a wine with 5 traits vs. 50: more traits capture nuance but take longer to record and compare.', 'Switching from a 1536-dim to a 768-dim embedding model halves your vector storage and speeds search, at some quality cost.', '[{"text":"A property of embeddings.","id":"embeddings"},{"text":"Affects storage and search in the vector database.","id":"vectordatabase"}]'::jsonb, 'Each embedding is a fixed-length list of floats; the length is its dimension. Higher dimensions can encode finer distinctions but cost more memory, slower comparisons, and can hit diminishing returns. Some newer models support "Matryoshka" truncation, letting you shorten vectors for cheaper search when full fidelity is not needed.', 'A direct lever on storage bill and latency; bigger is not automatically better.', 'Fixed float-vector length; scales memory and distance-compute linearly, with Matryoshka models allowing lossy truncation.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('vector-similarity', 'Vector Similarity', 'Similarity Measure', '', ARRAY['vector similarity','similarity measure']::text[], 'Core', 'The math for how "close" two embeddings are — the thing semantic search actually ranks by.', 'Measuring how alike two colors are by how near they sit on the color wheel.', 'A search ranks chunks by cosine similarity to the query embedding and returns the top few closest.', '[{"text":"Cosine similarity is the common choice.","id":"cosinesimilarity"},{"text":"Dot product is a faster variant.","id":"dot-product-search"}]'::jsonb, 'Once text is embedded, "relevance" becomes geometric distance. Cosine similarity (angle), dot product (angle and magnitude), and Euclidean distance are the usual measures, and the right one depends on whether your vectors are normalized. Retrieval quality can hinge on this choice, and mismatching the metric to the model is a classic silent bug.', 'An invisible but consequential setting; the wrong metric quietly degrades every search.', 'Distance/similarity function (cosine, dot, L2) over embeddings; must match the model’s training and normalization.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('dot-product-search', 'Dot Product Search', 'Inner Product Search', '', ARRAY['dot product search','inner product search','maximum inner product search']::text[], 'Rising', 'Ranking vectors by their dot product — fast, and equal to cosine when vectors are normalized.', 'Scoring how aligned two arrows are, rewarding both same-direction and longer arrows.', 'A vector DB configured for inner product returns matches slightly faster than cosine because it skips the normalization step.', '[{"text":"A specific vector similarity metric.","id":"vector-similarity"},{"text":"Equals cosine on normalized vectors.","id":"cosinesimilarity"}]'::jsonb, 'The dot product combines angle and magnitude, so longer vectors score higher even at the same direction. On unit-normalized embeddings it is mathematically identical to cosine similarity but cheaper to compute, which is why many indexes prefer it. On un-normalized vectors it behaves differently, and using it by accident is a subtle source of bad rankings.', 'A performance-friendly default when embeddings are normalized; otherwise a footgun.', 'Maximum inner product search; equivalent to cosine under L2 normalization, cheaper without the divide.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('euclidean-distance', 'Euclidean Distance', 'L2 Distance', '', ARRAY['euclidean distance','l2 distance']::text[], 'Core', 'Straight-line distance between two vectors — the everyday "how far apart" measure.', 'The as-the-crow-flies distance between two pins on a map.', 'A clustering job groups embeddings by L2 distance, putting vectors that sit physically near each other in the same bucket.', '[{"text":"One choice of vector similarity.","id":"vector-similarity"},{"text":"Contrasts with angle-based cosine.","id":"cosinesimilarity"}]'::jsonb, 'Euclidean (L2) distance is the square root of summed squared differences — the ruler-distance in vector space. It cares about magnitude, unlike cosine which cares only about direction, so on un-normalized embeddings the two can rank results quite differently. Many indexes support it, and for normalized vectors it produces the same ordering as cosine.', 'Another metric option; the point is to match it to how your embeddings were built.', 'sqrt(Σ(aᵢ−bᵢ)²); magnitude-sensitive, order-equivalent to cosine only under normalization.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('ivf-index', 'IVF Index', 'Inverted File Index', '', ARRAY['ivf index','inverted file index','ivf']::text[], 'Rising', 'A vector index that clusters data into buckets and only searches the few buckets near your query.', 'A warehouse split into aisles by category — you only walk the aisles that could hold what you want.', 'FAISS with an IVF index partitions a billion vectors into cells and probes just a handful, trading a little recall for big speed.', '[{"text":"An alternative to HNSW for ANN.","id":"hnsw"},{"text":"Often paired with product quantization.","id":"product-quantization"}]'::jsonb, 'IVF clusters vectors (via k-means) into cells and, at query time, searches only the nprobe nearest cells instead of everything. More probes means higher recall and slower search — a direct dial. It is frequently combined with product quantization to compress the vectors too, making it a workhorse for very large, memory-constrained collections.', 'Scales search to enormous datasets on a budget; recall is a tunable you must set deliberately.', 'k-means cell partitioning with nprobe-limited search; commonly IVF-PQ for compression at billion scale.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('product-quantization', 'Product Quantization', 'PQ', '', ARRAY['product quantization','pq']::text[], 'Rising', 'Compressing vectors into tiny codes so billions fit in memory, at a small accuracy cost.', 'Describing a paint color by the nearest name in a small swatch book instead of exact RGB values.', 'PQ shrinks a 1536-float vector into a handful of bytes, letting a single machine hold vectors that would otherwise need a cluster.', '[{"text":"Frequently combined with an IVF index.","id":"ivf-index"},{"text":"Trades memory for approximate nearest neighbor accuracy.","id":"approximate-nearest-neighbor"}]'::jsonb, 'Product quantization splits each vector into subvectors and replaces each with the ID of its nearest centroid from a small learned codebook, turning floats into bytes. Distances are then approximated from precomputed tables, fast and memory-light. The compression is lossy, so recall drops a bit — usually recovered by re-ranking the top candidates with their full vectors.', 'The reason massive vector search fits on modest hardware; expect a small, recoverable accuracy hit.', 'Subspace codebook quantization to byte codes with table-based distance; lossy, typically re-ranked with exact vectors.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('faiss', 'FAISS', 'Facebook AI Similarity Search', '“face”', ARRAY['faiss','facebook ai similarity search']::text[], 'Core', 'Meta’s open-source library for fast vector search — the toolbox many systems are built on.', 'The industrial engine you drop into your own car rather than machining pistons yourself.', 'A startup prototypes retrieval by loading embeddings into a FAISS index in a few lines instead of standing up a full database.', '[{"text":"Implements indexes like IVF and HNSW.","id":"ivf-index"},{"text":"A lower-level alternative to a full vector database.","id":"vectordatabase"}]'::jsonb, 'FAISS is a battle-tested C++/Python library offering flat, IVF, HNSW, and PQ indexes with GPU support. It is a library, not a service — you handle storage, persistence, and scaling yourself — which makes it ideal for research and embedding into products, less so for teams wanting a managed database. Many hosted vector DBs use FAISS-like algorithms under the hood.', 'Great for prototypes and custom builds; a managed vector DB may be less work in production.', 'Similarity-search library (flat/IVF/HNSW/PQ, CPU/GPU); you own persistence, sharding, and serving.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('pgvector', 'pgvector', 'Postgres Vector Extension', '', ARRAY['pgvector','postgres vector extension']::text[], 'Rising', 'A Postgres extension that lets your regular database do vector search, no separate system needed.', 'Adding a spice rack to the kitchen you already have instead of building a second kitchen.', 'A team stores embeddings in a new column and runs similarity queries with SQL, keeping vectors right next to their relational data.', '[{"text":"Turns Postgres into a vector database.","id":"vectordatabase"},{"text":"Supports HNSW and IVF indexes.","id":"hnsw"}]'::jsonb, 'pgvector adds a vector column type and similarity operators to PostgreSQL, with HNSW and IVFFlat indexing. Its big appeal is operational simplicity: one database for both structured data and embeddings, with familiar SQL, transactions, and joins. At very large scale or extreme QPS a dedicated vector DB may pull ahead, but for many apps pgvector is more than enough.', 'Often the pragmatic choice — one fewer system to run when you already use Postgres.', 'Vector type + HNSW/IVFFlat operators in Postgres; unifies relational and similarity queries at the cost of specialized scale.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('retrieval-pipeline', 'Retrieval Pipeline', 'RAG Pipeline', '', ARRAY['retrieval pipeline','rag pipeline']::text[], 'Core', 'The full assembly line from a user question to the passages handed to the model.', 'A kitchen line: prep the order, pull ingredients, plate it — each station feeding the next.', 'Query rewrite → embed → vector search → rerank → assemble context — a typical pipeline behind one chatbot reply.', '[{"text":"Wraps around the core retrieval step.","id":"retrieval"},{"text":"Query rewriting often sits at the front.","id":"query-rewriting"}]'::jsonb, 'Real retrieval is rarely one call; it is a sequence of stages — rewrite, expand, embed, search, filter, rerank, assemble — each of which can help or hurt. Treating it as a pipeline lets you measure and tune each stage independently, which is how teams debug "the answers are bad" into "reranking is dropping the right chunk". More stages add latency, so every one should earn its place.', 'Seeing retrieval as stages turns vague quality complaints into fixable, measurable steps.', 'Composable stages (rewrite→embed→search→filter→rerank→assemble); each is independently evaluable and a latency cost.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('ingestion', 'Ingestion', 'Indexing Pipeline', '', ARRAY['ingestion','indexing pipeline']::text[], 'Core', 'The one-time-ish job of loading documents in: parse, chunk, embed, and store them for later search.', 'Stocking the pantry before you cook — everything gets sorted and shelved so it is ready when you need it.', 'Nightly, new help articles are parsed, split into chunks, embedded, and written to the vector store so search stays current.', '[{"text":"Feeds the document store and index.","id":"document-store"},{"text":"Includes the chunking step.","id":"chunking"}]'::jsonb, 'Ingestion is the write side of retrieval: extract text (from PDFs, HTML, wherever), clean it, chunk it, embed the chunks, and persist vectors plus metadata. It is unglamorous but decisive — parsing errors, bad chunking, or stale data here poison every downstream query. Keeping it incremental and idempotent is what keeps a knowledge base fresh without full rebuilds.', 'Where data freshness and quality are won or lost; schedule and monitor it, don’t set-and-forget.', 'Parse→clean→chunk→embed→upsert; should be incremental and idempotent to keep the index current cheaply.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('embedding-cache', 'Embedding Cache', 'Vector Cache', '', ARRAY['embedding cache','vector cache']::text[], 'Rising', 'Saving embeddings you’ve already computed so you don’t pay to re-embed the same text.', 'Keeping receipts so you never re-do a calculation you already finished.', 'When the same paragraph appears in ten documents, the cache returns its stored vector instead of calling the embedding model ten times.', '[{"text":"Cuts cost during ingestion.","id":"ingestion"},{"text":"Avoids needless re-embedding.","id":"re-embedding"}]'::jsonb, 'Embedding calls cost money and time, and lots of text repeats or reappears unchanged. A cache keyed by a hash of the input (and model version) returns prior vectors instantly, which speeds ingestion and lowers bills. The subtlety is invalidation: if you change embedding models, the cache must be keyed by model too, or you’ll silently mix incompatible vectors.', 'A quiet cost-saver on large or frequently re-ingested corpora.', 'Content+model-hash keyed vector store; must invalidate on model change to avoid mixing embedding spaces.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('re-embedding', 'Re-embedding', 'Reindexing', '', ARRAY['re-embedding','reindexing']::text[], 'Rising', 'Recomputing all your embeddings — usually because you switched to a better embedding model.', 'Re-translating an entire library when you hire a better translator; the old translations no longer match.', 'Upgrading from an old embedding model to a new one forces re-embedding every chunk, since vectors from different models aren’t comparable.', '[{"text":"Often triggered by a new embedding model.","id":"embedding-model"},{"text":"Repeats much of the ingestion work.","id":"ingestion"}]'::jsonb, 'Embeddings from different models live in different vector spaces, so you cannot mix them — upgrading the model means re-embedding the whole corpus and rebuilding the index. It is a real operational cost and a reason to choose an embedding model carefully up front. Planning for it — versioning vectors, running old and new side by side during migration — avoids a painful big-bang cutover.', 'A hidden switching cost when adopting a new embedding model; budget time for it.', 'Full corpus re-vectorization on model change; spaces aren’t compatible, so plan versioned, side-by-side migration.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('context-assembly', 'Context Assembly', 'Prompt Assembly', '', ARRAY['context assembly','prompt assembly']::text[], 'Rising', 'Stitching retrieved passages, instructions, and history into the final prompt the model sees.', 'Plating a dish: arranging the retrieved ingredients in the right order so the meal makes sense.', 'The system slots the top 5 chunks, a system instruction, and the user question into a template, trimming to fit the context window.', '[{"text":"The last stage of the retrieval pipeline.","id":"retrieval-pipeline"},{"text":"Must respect the context window budget.","id":"contextwindow"}]'::jsonb, 'After retrieval, something has to decide the order, formatting, and token budget of everything that goes into the prompt — passages, citations, instructions, and history. Order matters (models weight the start and end more), as do deduplication and clear source markers for citation. Poor assembly can waste the good passages retrieval worked hard to find.', 'The final step that determines whether good retrieval actually turns into a good answer.', 'Template + ordering + token-budgeting of retrieved chunks and instructions; position, dedup, and source tagging all matter.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('citation-grounding', 'Citation Grounding', 'Answer Attribution', '', ARRAY['citation grounding','answer attribution']::text[], 'Rising', 'Making the model point to the exact source for each claim, so answers are checkable.', 'A term paper with footnotes — you can flip to the reference and confirm the writer didn’t make it up.', 'A research assistant answers "revenue grew 12%" with a clickable link to the sentence in the 10-K that says so.', '[{"text":"Builds on the broader idea of grounding.","id":"grounding"},{"text":"Related to source attribution.","id":"source-attribution"}]'::jsonb, 'Citation grounding ties each generated statement back to a retrieved passage, usually by having the model reference chunk IDs it was given. It boosts trust and makes hallucinations catchable, since a claim with no supporting source is a red flag. The hard part is faithfulness — models can cite a source that doesn’t actually support the claim, so citations reduce but do not eliminate the need to verify.', 'The feature that turns "trust me" into "check for yourself"; a big driver of user trust in RAG.', 'Claim-to-chunk linking via referenced IDs; improves verifiability but citation faithfulness itself must be checked.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('source-attribution', 'Source Attribution', 'Provenance', '', ARRAY['source attribution','provenance']::text[], 'Rising', 'Tracking and showing where each piece of an answer came from.', 'A recipe card noting which cookbook each step was adapted from.', 'An answer lists "Sources: Billing Policy §3, Onboarding Guide p.7" so a user knows exactly what informed it.', '[{"text":"The mechanism behind citation grounding.","id":"citation-grounding"},{"text":"Depends on metadata kept through ingestion.","id":"ingestion"}]'::jsonb, 'Attribution means every retrieved chunk carries provenance — document, section, URL, timestamp — through the pipeline so the final answer can name its sources. It supports citations, auditing, and access control, and it is only as good as the metadata captured at ingestion. Dropped provenance early on cannot be recovered later, which is why it is a design concern from the start.', 'Essential for regulated or high-trust domains where "says who?" must have an answer.', 'Propagate document/section/URL metadata end-to-end; provenance lost at ingestion is unrecoverable downstream.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('retrieval-augmentation', 'Retrieval Augmentation', 'Retrieval-Augmented Generation', '', ARRAY['retrieval augmentation']::text[], 'Core', 'The general move of feeding a model fetched facts at answer time instead of relying on its memory.', 'Handing a contestant the reference sheet before the quiz rather than trusting what they crammed.', 'Instead of fine-tuning a model on your policies, you retrieve the relevant policy text and paste it into the prompt each time.', '[{"text":"RAG is the best-known instance.","id":"rag"},{"text":"Reduces hallucination by grounding answers.","id":"hallucination"}]'::jsonb, 'Retrieval augmentation is the umbrella idea: rather than baking knowledge into weights, you fetch relevant information at inference and give it to the model as context. It keeps answers current and grounded, sidesteps expensive retraining, and localizes updates to the data. The trade is that quality now depends on retrieval, and every answer carries the token cost of its evidence.', 'Update knowledge by editing docs, not retraining models — cheaper and faster to keep current.', 'Inject fetched context at inference vs. parameterizing knowledge; shifts the quality bottleneck to retrieval.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('multi-vector-retrieval', 'Multi-Vector Retrieval', 'Multi-Representation Retrieval', '', ARRAY['multi-vector retrieval','multi-representation retrieval']::text[], 'Rising', 'Representing one document with several vectors instead of one, to capture more of its meaning.', 'Describing a house with separate photos of each room rather than a single blurry exterior shot.', 'A long document is stored as one vector per section, so a query can match the exact section it needs, not a mushy whole-doc average.', '[{"text":"ColBERT is a well-known approach.","id":"colbert"},{"text":"Refines ordinary dense retrieval.","id":"dense-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'A single embedding for a long or multi-topic document averages everything into one point, blurring specifics. Multi-vector retrieval keeps several embeddings per item — per chunk, per token, or per generated summary — so matching happens at finer grain. It improves recall and precision on complex content, at the cost of more storage and more vectors to search.', 'Helps when documents cover many topics and single-vector search feels imprecise.', 'Multiple embeddings per document (chunk/token/summary level); finer matching, higher index size and search cost.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('colbert', 'ColBERT', 'Contextualized Late Interaction over BERT', '“cole-bert”', ARRAY['colbert','contextualized late interaction over bert']::text[], 'Rising', 'A retrieval model that keeps a vector per word and matches them individually for sharper results.', 'Comparing two essays sentence by sentence instead of judging each by a single one-line summary.', 'ColBERT retrieves passages by matching each query token to its best-matching document token, catching nuances a single-vector search misses.', '[{"text":"The flagship late interaction method.","id":"late-interaction"},{"text":"A form of multi-vector retrieval.","id":"multi-vector-retrieval"}]'::jsonb, 'ColBERT embeds every token of query and document separately, then scores a pair by summing each query token’s best match against the document’s tokens — "late interaction". This retains fine-grained signal that single-vector encoders lose, boosting quality, especially on nuanced queries. The price is much larger indexes and heavier computation, which is why it is powerful but not always the default.', 'A quality upgrade for demanding search, weighed against bigger storage and infra cost.', 'Token-level embeddings with MaxSim late interaction; higher accuracy at the cost of large multi-vector indexes.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('late-interaction', 'Late Interaction', 'Late-Interaction Scoring', '', ARRAY['late interaction','late-interaction scoring']::text[], 'Rising', 'Comparing query and document at the token level only at the end, keeping detail a single vector loses.', 'Two teams working separately, then meeting at the last minute to match up their notes point by point.', 'Instead of collapsing a passage into one vector, late interaction keeps its token vectors and matches them against the query’s at scoring time.', '[{"text":"ColBERT is its best-known implementation.","id":"colbert"},{"text":"A middle ground between bi- and cross-encoders.","id":"bi-encoder"}]'::jsonb, '"Early interaction" (cross-encoders) feeds query and document together for max accuracy but can’t precompute anything. "No interaction" (bi-encoders) precomputes single vectors, fast but coarse. Late interaction splits the difference: encode separately and precompute token vectors, then do a lightweight fine-grained match at query time — much of the accuracy, much of the speed, at the cost of storage.', 'The design that buys near cross-encoder quality without cross-encoder latency.', 'Per-token precomputed vectors combined via MaxSim at query time; a precision/latency compromise between bi- and cross-encoders.', 'Retrieval & memory', 60, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('cross-encoder', 'Cross-Encoder', 'Cross Encoder', '', ARRAY['cross-encoder','cross encoder']::text[], 'Core', 'A model that reads query and document together to judge relevance — accurate, but too slow to search with.', 'A judge who reads both essays side by side before scoring, rather than grading each in isolation.', 'After fast search returns 100 candidates, a cross-encoder reranks them by reading each one next to the query, surfacing the true best few.', '[{"text":"The engine behind reranking.","id":"reranking"},{"text":"Contrasts with the faster bi-encoder.","id":"bi-encoder"}]'::jsonb, 'A cross-encoder takes the query and a candidate document as a single joint input, letting them attend to each other, and outputs one relevance score. That interaction makes it far more accurate than independent embeddings, but you must run it fresh for every pair — impossible over a whole corpus. So it lives in the reranking stage, scoring a small candidate set from a faster first-pass retriever.', 'The precision boost at the end of the pipeline; used on a shortlist, never the whole database.', 'Joint query-document encoding → single relevance score; O(candidates) cost confines it to reranking.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('bi-encoder', 'Bi-Encoder', 'Dual Encoder', '', ARRAY['bi-encoder','dual encoder']::text[], 'Core', 'A model that embeds query and document separately, so you can precompute and search millions fast.', 'Two people writing independent summaries, then comparing notes — quick, but they never actually read together.', 'A bi-encoder embeds every document once ahead of time; at query time you embed just the question and do a fast vector search.', '[{"text":"The basis of dense retrieval.","id":"dense-retrieval"},{"text":"Traded off against the accurate cross-encoder.","id":"cross-encoder"}]'::jsonb, 'A bi-encoder maps query and document to vectors independently, which is exactly what lets you embed the whole corpus in advance and retrieve with fast similarity search. The cost of that independence is missing fine-grained interactions between query and document, so it is less precise than a cross-encoder. The standard pattern pairs them: bi-encoder for fast recall, cross-encoder to rerank.', 'The workhorse that makes large-scale semantic search fast; usually backed by a reranker for precision.', 'Independent query/doc encoders enabling precomputed ANN; loses cross-attention precision, hence the rerank pairing.', 'Retrieval & memory', 80, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[]),
  ('reader', 'Reader', 'Reader Model', '', ARRAY['reader','reader model']::text[], 'Fading', 'The component that reads retrieved passages and produces the actual answer — in classic QA, the second half after the retriever.', 'The researcher who reads the pulled files and writes the summary, after the librarian fetches them.', 'In a retriever-reader system, the retriever finds 10 passages and the reader extracts "March 2021" as the answer to "when did it launch?".', '[{"text":"The counterpart to the retriever.","id":"retrieval"},{"text":"Largely absorbed into modern RAG generation.","id":"rag"}]'::jsonb, 'In the original retriever-reader design, the retriever surfaced candidate passages and a separate reader model extracted or generated the answer from them. Modern RAG blurs this: the LLM is the reader, generating rather than extracting, so the standalone "reader" term is fading. The division of labor still matters conceptually — finding evidence and using it are distinct jobs with distinct failure modes.', 'A useful mental split even now: retrieval finding the evidence vs. the model using it well.', 'The answer-producing stage after retrieval; in RAG it is the generative LLM, so the extractive "reader" is largely legacy.', 'Retrieval & memory', 30, ARRAY['seed','retrieval-memory']::text[])
